<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ871109-0055 </DOCNO><HL> Sterling Drug Inc.Plans to Buy BackUp to 3 Million Shares</HL><DD> 11/09/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> STYBUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK) </IN><DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sterling Drug Inc. said it plans to buy back as many as three million, or 5.3%, of its common shares.    At current market prices, the buy-back would cost the pharmaceuticals and consumer-products company $162 million. Sterling's shares closed Friday at $54, up 12.5 cents, in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.    The company called the buy-back a good investment. About 57 million Sterling shares are outstanding.    As a result of the recent collapse in stock prices, many companies have been buying back shares.    Here is a list of concerns that announced buy-back programs recently:    Americana Hotels andamp; Realty Corp., Automatic Data Processing Inc., Deluxe Check Printers Inc., Engelhard Corp., ICM Property Investors Inc., I.R.E. Financial Corp., Nortek Inc., Skyline Chili Inc., South Carolina National Corp., Stocker andamp; Yale Inc., Temple-Inland Inc., UniCare Financial Corp. </TEXT></DOC>